'''Ghost-canceling reference''' ('''GCR''') is a special sub-signal on a [[television]] [[television channel|channel]] that receivers can use to attenuate the [[ghosting (television)|ghosting]] effect of a television signal split into [[Multipath propagation|multiple paths]] between transmitter and receiver. 

In the [[United States]], the GCR signal is a [[chirp]] in [[frequency]] of the [[modulating signal]] from 0 Hz to 4.2 MHz, transmitted during the [[vertical blanking interval]] over one video line (line 19 in the U.S.), shifted in phase by 180° once per frame, with this pattern inverted every four lines. Television receivers generate their own local versions of this signal, and use the comparison between the local and remote signals to tune out any ghost images on the screen.

GCR was introduced after its recommendation in 1993 by the Advanced Television Systems Committee.<ref>http://www.museum.tv/eotv/advancedtele.htm</ref>

{{reflist}}

==External links==
*[http://atsc.org/standard/a49-ghost-canceling-reference-signal-for-ntsc/ Official GCR specification]

{{Video formats}}
[[Category:Television technology]]


{{tv-tech-stub}}

'''Java Pacific Film''' (alternatively, '''Java Pasific Film''') was a short-lived film production company that helped make significant contributions to [[Indonesian cinema]] in the 1930s.
==Background== During 1934 and early 1935, all feature films released in the [[Dutch East Indies]] had been directed by [[The Teng Chun]], based on [[Chinese mythology]] or martial arts, and targeted at low-class audiences, generally [[Chinese Indonesians|ethnic Chinese]].{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=380–381}} This situation was created by the [[Great Depression]], which had led to the Dutch East Indies government collecting higher taxes, advertisers asking for more money, and cinemas selling tickets at lower prices; this ensured that there was a very low [[profit margin]] for local films. During this period cinemas in the country mainly showed [[Hollywood]] productions.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=145}}
==History== Java Pacific Film was founded in 1934 in [[Bandoeng]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmmuseum.nl/bedrijf/java-pacific-film|title=Java Pacific Film bij Film in Nederland|publisher=[[EYE Film Institute Netherlands]]|accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref> in what was then the [[Dutch East Indies]], by Dutch-Indonesian journalist [[Albert Balink]] working with the [[Wong brothers]]. Balink, who intended to target high-class audiences, had found financial support for the new company, took control, while the Wongs brought a studio and film equipment to the endeavour. The studio, an old [[tapioca flour]] factory, featured simple film editing equipment, several buildings to serve as living quarters for the employees, and a veranda surrounded by trees used for editing.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=156}} The smokestack had the company's initials, JPF, in large letters.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=156}} Their first production was a documentary about [[Mount Merapi]], entitled ''De Merapi Dreight'' (''Mount Merapi Looms''), in 1934.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=165}}
Dutch filmmaker [[Mannus Franken]] was brought to the country in 1934 to help make the movie ''[[Pareh]]'' between 1934 and 1936.<ref name="HjortMacKenzie2000">{{cite book|last=Roberts|first=Martin|editor=Hjort Mette|others=Scott MacKenzie|title=Cinema and Nation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B9_JeRIL-UcC&pg=PA164|accessdate=23 July 2012|year=2000|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=9780415208635|pages=162–76|chapter=Indonesia: The Movie}}</ref> Franken had previously had success with documentary filmmaking in the Netherlands.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=159}} The production cost 75,000 [[Netherlands Indies gulden|gulden]], with its star [[Rd. Mochtar]] receiving 250 gulden monthly.{{sfn|Biran|2009|p=162}} A commercial flop which bankrupted the producers and company,{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=161–62}} ''Pareh'' is credited with shifting the focus of Indonesian cinema from Chinese productions and subject matter to a more local industry. The film is also praised for its cinematic quality.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=8MpnoVvnB5cC |title=Cinema: A Visual Anthropology |isbn=978-1-84520-793-9 |last1=Gray |first1=Gordon |date=2010 |publisher=Berg |location=Oxford}}</ref> and its audio.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pareh, een rijstlied van Java |url=http://www.filmmuseum.nl/en/film/pareh-een-rijstlied-van-java?quicktabs_2=2 |work=filmmuseum.nl |publisher=[[EYE Film Institute Netherlands]] |location=Amsterdam |date=20 October 2011 |accessdate=23 July 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69MxyYcIp?url=http://www.filmmuseum.nl/en/film/pareh-een-rijstlied-van-java?quicktabs_2=2 |archivedate=23 July 2012 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite thesis |type=Bachelour's of History Thesis |chapter=Sekilas Perkembangan Perfilman di Indonesia |trans-chapter=An Overview of the Development of Film in Indonesia |language=Indonesian |title=Kebijakan Pemerintahan Orde Baru Terhadap Perfilman Indonesia Tahun 1966–1980 |trans-title=New Order Policy Towards Indonesian Films (1966–1980) |last=Prayogo |first=Wisnu Agung |year=2009 |publisher=University of Indonesia}}</ref>
==Successor== Balink collected funds from numerous sponsors and established the Dutch Indies Film Syndicate ({{lang|nl|Algemeen Nederlandsch Indisch Filmsyndicaat}}, or ANIF) in late 1936.{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=165–166}} This government-owned<ref name="SenHill2006">{{cite book|last1=Sen|first1=Krishna|last2=Hill|first2=David T.|title=Media, Culture and Politics in Indonesia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xMhWm38KQcsC&pg=PA138|accessdate=24 July 2012|year=2006|publisher=Equinox |isbn=9789793780429|page=138}}</ref> company involved all major figures from JPF.{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=167–168}} Working mostly on [[newsreel]]s and documentaries,{{sfn|Biran|2009|pp=165–166}} in 1937 it produced the commercial success ''[[Terang Boelan]]''.<ref name="Slobin2008">{{cite book|last=Slobin|first=Mark|title=Global Soundtracks: Worlds of Film Music|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VQw5Ci7sbasC&pg=PA217|accessdate=24 July 2012|year=2008|publisher=Wesleyan UP|isbn=9780819568823|page=217}}</ref> In 1938 it released Franken's documentary ''[[Tanah Sabrang]]'' and in 1940 closed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jakarta.go.id/web/encyclopedia/detail/793/Algemeen-Nederlandsch-Indisch-Filmsyndicaat-ANIF |title=Algemeen Nederlandsch Indisch Filmsyndicaat (ANIF) |language=Indonesian |work=Jakarta City Government |publisher=Jakarta City Government |archivedate=25 July 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69POqEHa0?url=http://www.jakarta.go.id/web/encyclopedia/detail/793/Algemeen-Nederlandsch-Indisch-Filmsyndicaat-ANIF |accessdate=25 July 2012 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
