{{for|the actor|Patrick Gilmore (actor)}} {{Infobox person | name = Patrick Gilmore | image = Patrick S. Gilmore.jpg | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date|1829|12|25|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[Ballygar]], [[County Galway]], Ireland | death_date = {{death date and age|1892|9|24|1829|12|25|mf=y}} | death_place = [[St. Louis, Missouri]], U.S. | occupation = [[Composer]], [[Military band|bandmaster]], [[soldier]] | spouse = Ellen O'Neill (m. 1858) | children = Minnie L. Gilmore }}
'''Patrick Sarsfield Gilmore''' (December 25, 1829 – September 24, 1892) was an [[Ireland|Irish]]-born [[Americans|American]] [[composer]] and [[Military band|bandmaster]] who lived and worked in the [[United States]] after 1848.<ref name=obit/> Whilst serving in the [[Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], Gilmore wrote the lyrics to the song "[[When Johnny Comes Marching Home]]." This was published under the pseudonym Louis Lambert in September 1863.
==Life and career== Gilmore was born in [[Ballygar]], [[County Galway]]. He started his [[music]] career at age fifteen, and spent time in [[Canada]] with an [[England|English]] band.<ref>{{Cite Appletons'|wstitle=Gilmore, Patrick Sarsfield|year=1900}}</ref> He settled in [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]] in 1848, becoming leader of the Suffolk, [[Boston Brigade Band|Boston Brigade]], and Salem bands in swift succession. He also worked in the Boston music store of [[John P. Ordway]] and founded [[Ordway's Aeolians]], a group of [[blackface]] [[Minstrel show|minstrel]]s.<ref>[http://www.ibiblio.org/fiddlers/SAIL_SALLO.htm Gilmore as minstrel player]</ref> With the Salem Band, Gilmore performed at the 1857 inauguration of President [[James Buchanan]].
[[Image:Front Piazza of Grand Hotel, 4 P.M. with Gilmore's Boston Band, Saratoga, N.Y, by Hall Bros..jpg|thumb|left|"Front Piazza of [[Grand Union Hotel (Saratoga Springs, New York)|Grand Hotel]], 4 P.M. with Gilmore's Boston Band, [[Saratoga Springs, New York|Saratoga, N.Y.]]," mid-19th century]]
In 1858 he founded "Gilmore's Band," and at the outset of war the band enlisted with the [[24th Massachusetts Volunteers]], accompanying [[Ambrose Burnside|General Burnside]] to [[North Carolina]]. After the temporary discharge of bands from the field, [[John Albion Andrew|Governor Andrew]] of Massachusetts entrusted Gilmore with the task of re-organizing military music-making, and General [[Nathaniel P. Banks]] created him Bandmaster-general.
When peace resumed, Gilmore was asked to organize a celebration, which took place at [[New Orleans]]. That success emboldened him to undertake two major music festivals at Boston, the [[National Peace Jubilee]] in 1869 and the [[World's Peace Jubilee and International Musical Festival]] in 1872. These featured monster orchestras of massed bands<ref>{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Gilmore, Patrick Sarsfield}}</ref> with the finest singers and instrumentalists (including the only American appearance by "[[waltz|waltz king]]" [[Johann Strauss II]]) and cemented Gilmore's reputation as the leading musical figure of the age. Coliseums were erected for the occasions, holding 60- and 120,000 persons. Grateful Bostonians presented Gilmore with medals and cash, but in 1873 he moved to [[New York City]], as bandmaster of the 22nd Regiment. Gilmore took this band on acclaimed tours of Europe.
It was back on home soil, preparing an 1892 musical celebration of the [[quadricentennial]] anniversary of [[Christopher Columbus]]' voyage of discovery, that Gilmore collapsed and died in [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]].<ref name=obit>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=A Noted Bandmaster Gone. Patrick Sarsfield Gilmore Dies In St. Louis. |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1892/09/25/104146208.pdf |quote=Stricken With Death After But One Day's Illness. Heart Disease Pronounced To Be The Cause. The News A Great Surprise To The Admirers Of The Popular Leader. The Remains To Be Brought To This City. Patrick Sarsfield Gilmore, the celebrated bandmaster, died suddenly at 6:40 o'clock this evening at the Lindell Hotel after an illness of one day. Heart disease was the cause of death. |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=September 25, 1892 |accessdate=2013-12-27 }}</ref> Patrick S. Gilmore was buried in [[Calvary Cemetery (Queens, New York)]].<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=eLWao2lIGTEC&pg=PA489&lpg=PA489&dq=patrick+gilmore+calvary+cemetery&source=bl&ots=1nFnLyxZBb&sig=O5oTzsUq_wMOSc2worBf5RfeysA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwii5vWasrveAhUMGnwKHf_aBAE4ChDoATAFegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=patrick%20gilmore%20calvary%20cemetery&f=false ''Where They're Buried'']</ref>
==Legacy== {{listen|filename=Famous 22nd Regiment March - U.S. Marine Band.ogg|title=Famous 22nd Regiment March|description=Gilmore's "Famous 22nd Regiment March" (1874), played by the [[United States Marine Band]]}} In many ways Gilmore can be seen as the principal figure in 19th-century American music. He was a composer, the "Famous 22nd Regiment March" from 1874 is just one example. He held the first "Promenade Concert in America" in 1855, the forerunner to today's [[Boston Pops]]. He set up "Gilmore's Concert Garden", which became [[Madison Square Garden (1879)|Madison Square Garden]]. He was the Musical Director of the Nation in effect, leading the festivities for the 1876 Centennial celebrations in Philadelphia and the dedication of the [[Statue of Liberty]] in 1886. In 1888 he started the tradition of seeing in the [[New Year]] in [[Times Square]]. {{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}
In 1891, he played for some of [[Thomas Edison]]'s first commercial recordings. Musically, he was the first arranger to set brass instruments against the reeds, which remains the basis for [[big band]] orchestration. His arrangements of contemporary classics did a great deal to familiarize the American people with the work of the great European musical masters. {{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}
Patrick Sarsfield Gilmore was inducted into the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]] in 1970.
