{{Use Australian English|date=August 2015}}
{{About|the 3D audio company|the patent holding company|Personal Audio LLC (Patent holding company)}}
{{refimprove|date=July 2013}}

'''Personal Audio Pty Ltd,''' incorporated on 1 March 2007, is a provider of 3D audio technology solutions applied into [[video games]], music listening and [[VOIP]] telecommunications. The company focuses principally on solutions that are complementary to existing technologies and leverages off the research originally carried out at the Auditory Neuroscience Laboratory at the [[University of Sydney]], [[Australia]]. The company has received seed investment from Allen and Buckeridge{{fact|date=August 2014}} and is headquartered in Sydney.  

==MyEars Surround Audio==
Their first product, MyEars, launched in beta test on 14 July 2010,<ref name="PCWorld">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcworld.idg.com.au/article/353333/3d_audio_serenade_gamers|title=3D audio to serenade gamers|author=Spandas Lui|date=4 January 2015|work=PC World|accessdate=3 January 2015}}</ref> is a web based audio profiling service that creates 7.1 [[surround sound]] over headphones that is individualised to the listener. The [[3D audio effect]] rendering process is quite standard;{{fact|date=August 2014}} however, the profiling service uses a hearing localisation test to make a prediction of the ear shape of the listener and generates individualized Head Related Transfer Functions ([[HRTF]]s) for the right and left ears. These are downloaded to the user's gaming PC. The audio rendering is carried out using [[FMOD]] by Firelight Technology using either a dedicated client (MyEars-Connect) that sits between the video game and the operating system or directly in-game if FMOD is utilised as the game audio engine.

The MyEars service completed beta testing in early September and was launched on 19 September 2010. Reviews have been generally positive.<ref name = "GameOnNet">[http://games.on.net/article/10009/MyEars_Ears-On_Delivering_3D_Audio_via_Stereo_Headphones Test Review of MyEars on game.on.net ([[Internode ISP]].])</ref><ref name="APC">[http://apcmag.com/amazing-sound-for-gamers  Comparison between MyEars and Dolby Headphone ([[APC (magazine)]]]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }})</ref><ref name="Junglistpost">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamearena.com.au/videos/latest.php/bigpond-gamearena-5-inch-floppy-4--my-ears|title=Gaming on Google Play|publisher=|accessdate=3 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815131921/http://www.gamearena.com.au/videos/latest.php/bigpond-gamearena-5-inch-floppy-4--my-ears#|archive-date=15 August 2013|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This development has been cited by the International Society for Presence Research<ref name= "ISPR">[http://sct.temple.edu/blogs/ispr/2010/11/19/myears-improves-gaming-surround-sound/ MyEars in "Presence in the News"]</ref> (see [[Presence (telepresence)]]). The company reports a growing user base.<ref name = "PA website">[http://www.personalaudio.com.au Personal Audio News and Events]</ref>

